Systematic analysis of potential adeno-associated virus variants used in gene therapy¶

by Yao Chen --- Aug 16, 2023¶

This project is designed to analyze nextseq data GSE139657 derived from Church's lab published by Ogden P, Kelsic E, Sinai S, Church G https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/geo/query/acc.cgi?acc=GSE139657. The purpose is to identify the possible optimal AAV variants for gene therapy based on single variant introduced to the wildtype AAV2. The optimal variants should have few unqiue properties including evade the immune response, superior packaging ability and high tissue specficity.¶

Data Process¶

The experimental data for this project is downloaded from https://github.com/churchlab/AAV_fitness_landscape/tree/master/data/dataframes which is generated from a high impact factor research project "Comprehensive AAV capsid fitness landscape reveals a viral gene and enables machine-guided design"

Effort has been made to retreive the raw data and the following steps are performed.

  1. Access and installed the SRA tool from the project https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Traces/study/?acc=SRP227810&o=acc_s%3Aa
  2. Raw data were downloaded from SRA repository to google cloud platform

However, due to the size of the data I was not able to proceed it locally with my PC, the raw data were downloaded to google cloud plateform with significant delay and initial downloaded files name were not compatible with the metadata. Hence this project used the semi-processed data from github repository for this project.

# Determine the number of clusters based on elbow method
n=12
sse = []
for k in range(1, n, 1):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, max_iter=200).fit(X)
    sse.append(kmeans.inertia_)

plt.plot(range(1, n), sse)
plt.title("Elbow Method")
plt.xlabel("Number of Clusters")
plt.ylabel("SSE")
plt.show()
